Following script causes crash on live reload. The array holds node handles and they are not destroyed immediately when being removed from the scene; rather the ScriptInstance components remain as stale event receivers.

```
class Crasher : ScriptObject
{
    void Start()
    {
        Node@ checkNode = scene.GetChild("Check", true);
        if (checkNode is null)
            return;

        Array<Node@> checkNodes = scene.GetNodesWithTag("CheckZone");
        for (int n = 0; n < checkNodes.length; n++)
        {
            checkNode.RemoveChild(checkNodes[n]);
        }

        for (int i = 0; i < 5; ++i)
        {
            Node@ checkZoneNode = checkNode.CreateChild("CheckZone_" + i);
            checkZoneNode.CreateScriptObject(scriptFile, "CheckZone");
            checkZoneNode.AddTag("CheckZone");
        }
    }
}


class CheckZone : ScriptObject
{
    int checkZoneId = 1;
    bool isChecked = false;
}
```

According to the comment above the `VariantValue` the structure should not exceed 16 bytes in size. Which holds true on 32 bit platforms. However, on 64 bit platforms, because each sub union includes a pointer, the size of the structure doubles in size. And the other pointers except the first one `ptr_` are actually never used in code. Actually, even keeping just `ptr_` inside the first union pushes the structure size to 24 bytes on 64 bits. Should be 20 bytes but probably needs to satisfy alignment.

I suppose the entire union could be summed to:

```
union VariantValue
{
    int                 int_[4];
    float               float_[4];
    void *              ptr_; // or ptr_[16 / sizeof(ptr)]?
    bool                bool_;
};
```

Or this way to keep the naming:

```
union VariantValue
{
    struct { int int_, int2_, int3_, int4_; };
    struct { float float_, float2_, float3_, float4_; };
    void * ptr_;
    bool bool_;
};
```

If this was the intended behavior then please ignore this.

EDIT: I just realized that because of this, `float2_` will have an offset of 4 bytes from `float_` and same with `int2_` and `int_`. Which could get in the way of how they're used to represent Vectors, Quaternions etc.
